Functions

In programming, functions are used to automate or repeat common tasks.

A function can have multiple arguments. For example the mean() function accepts three arguments:

  • x which is a vector of numbers for which to calculate the mean
  • trim which is an optional argument to specify numbers to be ignored when calculating the mean
  • na.rm which is again an optional argument indicating whether missing values should be removed before calculating the mean

The arguments of a function are documented in the functions documentation. Here you can find more information about the function including examples. You can access the documentation of a function by writing a question mark in front of it.

?mean
## starting httpd help server ... done

Note that the arguments trim and na.rm both have a default value (0 and FALSE respectively). This means the arguments are optional and dont need to be specified when using the function.

For example:

vector <- c(1, 2, 3, NA)

mean(vector)
## [1] NA
mean(vector, na.rm = FALSE)
## [1] NA
mean(vector, na.rm = TRUE)
## [1] 2

Exercise 2Predicting the Output of a Function

Look up the arguments of the log() function. Then, predict which of the following calls does not return an error:

  • log(x = 100, 10)
  • log(100)
  • log(base = exp(1))
  • log(exp(1) ^ 3, exp(1))
  • log(base = 10, x = 100)
# Required arguments of the log() function:
# - x

# Optional arguments of the log() function:
# - base (defaults to exp(1))

# This function should work as the required argument is provided and base is
# given as a second argument
log(x = 100, 10)
## [1] 2
# This function should work because the required argument x is provided
log(100)
## [1] 4.60517
# This function should not work because x is not given
# log(base = exp(1))

# This function should work as both x and base are implicitly provided
log(exp(1) ^ 3, exp(1))
## [1] 3
# This function should work because both arguments are explicitly provided which
# is important because of the altered order
log(base = 10, x = 100)
## [1] 2

The key takeaway from this exercise is that the order of the arguments provided matters when the specific arguments used are not explicitly specified (log(100) instead of log(x = 100)).

Creating a Custom Function

We can create our own function using the function command. Lets make a function that accepts a vector x and returns the square of the vector.

square <- function(x) {
  x * x
}

The function square returns the square of the elements of an input vector x:

square(2)
## [1] 4
a <- 3
square(a)
## [1] 9
b <- c(1, 3)
square(b)
## [1] 1 9

R treats all variables as vectors as the example above shows.

Just like the mean() and the log() functions we examined above, we can pass multiple arguments to our custom function.

square_plus <- function(x, y = 1) {
  x * x + y
}

square_plus(3, 6)
## [1] 15
square_plus(3)
## [1] 10

The function above takes in two input variables and returns a single output. Thereby the argumentx is required and y optional which defaults to 1 if it is not explicitly specified.

Exercise 3Writing a Custom Function

Create a function called paste_together that takes two variables as input and pastes them together with the R base function paste.

paste_together <- function(x, y) {
  # This function pastes two strings together
  
  paste(x, y)
}

# Testing the function
paste_together("house number", 45)
## [1] "house number 45"
paste_together("letter", LETTERS)

The For Loop

According to Wikipedia:

In computer science, a for-loop (or simply for loop) is a control flow statement for specifying iteration, which allows code to be executed repeatedly. []

A for-loop has two parts: a header specifying the iteration, and a body which is executed once per iteration. The header often declares an explicit loop counter or loop variable, which allows the body to know which iteration is being executed. For-loops are typically used when the number of iterations is known before entering the loop.

For example:

for (i in 1:10) {
  print(i)
}
## [1] 1
## [1] 2
## [1] 3
## [1] 4
## [1] 5
## [1] 6
## [1] 7
## [1] 8
## [1] 9
## [1] 10

Exercise 4Using a For Loop

Create a function that calls the function squared_plus() from before for the numbers x to x + 10 and adds the results returning the total.

loop_function <- function(x) {
  total <- 0
  
  for (i in x:(x + 10)) {
    total <- total + square_plus(i)
  }
  
  return(total)
}

# Testing the function
loop_function(2)
## [1] 660

Exercise 5A Function to Calcuate the Variance

The variance of a set of numbers \(X\) is a statistic (a number that is derived from other numbers using a statistical procedure or algorithm) that quantifies the amount of spread in the values. Informally, it measures how far a set of numbers is spread out from its average value.

\[ \text{Variance}(X) = \text{Mean}(X^2) - (\text{Mean}(X))^2 \]

Create a function that calculates the variance of a numeric vector.

variance <- function(x) {
  mean(x ^ 2) - mean(x) ^ 2
}

Test the function on the vector vec. It should return the same answers as the built-in base R var function after applying the Bessels correction. This correction is simply multiplying the answer by \(N/(N+1)\), where \(N\) is the length of vec (i.e.the number of values in vec).

vec <- c(2, 4, 3, 6)

N <- length(vec)
corr <- N / (N - 1)

result <- variance(vec) * corr
result
## [1] 2.916667
test <- var(vec)
test
## [1] 2.916667
result == test
## [1] TRUE

When Should I Use Functions?

Code repetition is a good signal for when to use a function. As soon as you start copying and re-using code it makes sense to turn that chunk of code into a function.

For example, suppose we are interested in global exports of clothing in 2018. Which countries are the top exporting countries and to which countries do they export to?

Exercise 6Loading the Data

Load the trade.rds data set using readRDS(). Then, filter all entries from the year 2018. How many distinct countries does the data set contain?

trade_2018 <- readRDS("data/trade.rds") %>%
  filter(year == 2018)

head(trade_2018)
length(unique(trade_2018$reporter_iso))
## [1] 225

Lets start by analyzing China which is the country with the largest clothing exports.

temp <- trade_2018 %>%
  # Select China as the reporter
  filter(reporter_iso == "chn") %>%
  # Group by year
  group_by(year) %>%
  # Select the 5 largest trading partners with China measured by the export
  # value in USD
  slice_max(order_by = export_value_usd, n = 5)

# Extract the country names from the data set
country_name <- unique(temp$reporter_fullname_english)

plot_title <- paste("Top Five Countries that",
                    country_name,
                    "Exports Clothing To")

ggplot(data = temp, mapping = aes(x = reorder(partner_fullname_english,
                                              export_value_usd),
                                  y = export_value_usd)) +
  geom_point() +
  expand_limits(y = 0) +
  ggtitle(plot_title) +
  xlab("Importing Country") +
  ylab("Exporting Value (Billon US Dollar)") +
  coord_flip()

Suppose we want to make a similar plot for a list of countries. Lets say we are interested in India (ind), Bangladesh (bgd), Italy (ita) and Germany (deu) in addition to China.

Lets turn the code that generates the plot into a function.

Exercise 7Using a Function to Plot Data

Turn the previous code chunk into a function that takes the data set and a country code as arguments and creates a plot similar to the one above for the supplied country.

plot_top_five_partner_countries <- function(df, country_code) {
  temp <- df %>%
  # Select the provided country as the reporter
  filter(reporter_iso == country_code) %>%
  # Group by year
  group_by(year) %>%
  # Select the 5 largest trading partners measured by the export value in USD
  slice_max(order_by = export_value_usd, n = 5)

  # Extract the country names from the data set
  country_name <- unique(temp$reporter_fullname_english)

  plot_title <- paste("Top Five Countries that",
                      country_name,
                      "Exports Clothing To")

  ggplot(data = temp, mapping = aes(x = reorder(partner_fullname_english,
                                                export_value_usd),
                                    y = export_value_usd)) +
    geom_point() +
    expand_limits(y = 0) +
    ggtitle(plot_title) +
    xlab("Importing Country") +
    ylab("Exporting Value (Billon US Dollar)") +
    coord_flip()
}

Lets see if it works by creating the plot for Germany.

plot_top_five_partner_countries(trade_2018, country_code = "deu")

Now we can use a for loop to plot every country in a given vector.

countries <- c("bgd", "chn", "deu", "ind", "ita")

Exercise 8A Plot for Every Country

Write a for loop that calls the plot_top_five_partner_countries() function for each country in countries. Use the length() function to obtain the number of times the loop needs to be executed.

for (country in 1:length(countries)) {
  print(
    plot_top_five_partner_countries(df = trade_2018,
                                    country_code = countries[country])
  )
}
